response:
The inequality is undefined when $x = -5$, so we need to consider the intervals determined by $x = -5$ and the factors of the numerator (\(x^2 - 25\)).</think> <answer>Simplifying the inequality, we get
\[\frac{(x+5)(x-5)}{x+5} < 0.\]
The factors of the numerator split the real line into intervals. Considering each separately:



\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (2,0) (first) {};
\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (8,0) (second) {};
\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (14,0) (third) {};
\node[draw=cyan,minimum size=4] at (5,-4) {\(x<-5\)};

\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (2,-2) (fourth) {};
\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (8,-2) (fifth) {};
\node[draw=cyan,minimum size=4] at (5,-5) {\\(5<x \le 5\)};

\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (14,-2) (sixth) {};
\node[draw,circle,minimum size=4,半径=1cm] at (30,0) (seventh) {};
\node[draw=cyan,minimum size=4] at (25,-4) {$x>5$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

Note that $\frac{x-5}{x+5}$ is positive in $(6; +\infty)$, because it is positive there.
Also, \(\frac{1}{x-5}\) is negative in $(-5;5)$ and finite.
Thus, the only interval where it is finite and negative is $(-5;5)$.
Thus, only values in $(-5;5)$ will make the given expression finite.
Only values in $-5$ to $5$ will make the expression between $0$ and $1$.
Thus, $-5 < x < 5$ is the answer.
</answer>

problem:
In the figure shown, arc $ADB$ and arc $BEC$ are semicircles, each with a radius of one unit. Point $D$, point $E$ and point $F$ are the midpoints of arc $ADB$, arc $BEC$ and arc $DFE$, respectively. If arc $DFE$ is also a semicircle, what is the area of the shaded region?

[asy]
unitsize(0.5inch);
path t=(1,1)..(2,0)--(0,0)..cycle;
draw(t);
path r=shift((2,0))*t;
path s=shift((1,1))*t;
draw(s);
fill(s,gray(0.7));
fill((1,0)--(1,1)--(3,1)--(3,0)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill(t,white);
fill(r,white);
draw(t);
draw(r);
dot((0,0));
dot((1,1));
dot((2,2));
dot((3,1));
dot((2,0));
dot((4,0));
label("$A$",(0,0),W);
label("$B$",(2,0),S);
label("$C$",(4,0),E);
label("$D$",(1,1),NW);
label("$E$",(3,1),NE);
label("$F$",(2,2),N);
[/asy]

